# Readme conventions

When writing a readme document, it is most important to keep the file concise, i.e. short, well structured and understandable. 

Avoid using emojis. Prefer bullet points and script snippets over long text blocks.

- Before making any changes to the readme, make sure that the information you want to add is up to date and correct.
- After changing the readme, review it and make sure it
  - is well structured
  - contains every information exactly once (deduplicate)
  - is readable for humans

The Readme should start with a one paragraph text summary of the projects purpose.

This short summary should be followed by a very high level overview of what to find where in the repository. The Overview should answer the questions: Where can the reader find more detailed documentation/information? DOes this project have sub projects/modules, like separate folders for frontend, backend, helm charts, etc. Where are the CI/CD/Deployment related files like Dockerfiles, pipeline specifications, release scripts, etc.?

Then a usage section should explain 
- url(s) to access deployed stage(s)
- how to get a local dev setup running





